655	138	General syntax of extended inline assembly is as follows:	text	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.566474	1
656	138	__asm__(\n    assembler code\n    : output operands\n    : input operands\n    : list of clobbered registers\n);	code	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.58775	2
657	138	* After the assembler code, additional and optional information is used.\n* Instruction orders must be respected.	text	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.608006	3
658	138	__asm__(\n    ".intel_syntax noprefix;"\n    "mov rbx, rdx;"\n    "imul rbx, rcx;"\n    "mov rax, rbx;"\n    :"=a"(eproduct)\n    :"d"(x), "c"(y)\n    :"rbx"\n);	text	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.628942	4
659	138	printf("The extended inline product is %i\\\\n", eproduct);	code	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.650026	5
660	138	`a`, `d`, `c` are register constraints, and they map to the registers `rax`, `rdx`, `rcx`, respectively.\n`:"=a"(eproduct)` means that the output will be in `rax`, and `rax` will refer to the variable `eproduct`. Register `rdx` refers to `x`, and `rcx` refers to `y`, which are the input variables.\n`rbx` is considered clobbered in the code and will be restored to its original value, because it was declared in the list of clobbering registers.	text	txt	2024-07-28 09:57:22.670989	6
