5461	1623	The first method is to add users to a predefined administrators group and then, if it hasnt already been done, to configure the sudo policy to allow that group to do its job.\nIts simple enough to do except that different Linux distro families use different admin groups.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.613589	1
5462	1623	On Unix, BSD, and most Linux systems, you would add users to the **wheel** group.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.63377	2
5463	1623	Edit sudo policy file by doing `sudo visudo`:	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.654201	3
5464	1623	%wheel ALL=(ALL) ALL	code	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.674439	4
5465	1623	The percent sign indicates that were working with a group.\nThe three appearances of *ALL* mean that members of that group can perform *ALL* commands, as *ALL* users, on *ALL* machines in the network on which this policy is deployed.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.694946	5
5466	1623	%wheel ALL=(ALL) NOPASSWD: ALL	code	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.715661	6
5467	1623	The former snippet means that members of the **wheel** group would be able to perform all of their sudo tasks without ever having to enter any password.\nAvoid doing so, even for home use.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:17.736437	7
5468	1624	On Red Hat distros add users to the **wheel** group:	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.194615	1
5469	1624	sudo usermod -a -G wheel maggie	code	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.214518	2
5470	1624	Use `-a` option in order to prevent removing the user from other groups to which he or she belongs.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.234009	3
5471	1624	You can also add a user account to the wheel group as you create it.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.253925	4
5472	1624	sudo useradd -G wheel frank	code	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.273602	5
5473	1624	For members of the Debian family, including Ubuntu, the procedure is the same, except that you would use the **sudo** group instead of the **wheel** group.	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.294523	6
5474	1625	With a member of the Red Hat family, `useradd` comes with predefined default settings to create user accounts.\nFor non-Red Hat-type distros, youd need to either reconfigure the default settings or use extra option switches in order to create the users home directory and to assign the correct shell:	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.739936	1
5475	1625	*Red Hat distros*	text	txt	2024-07-28 10:10:18.760439	2
